<div id="average-facebook-ads-conversion-rates-by-industry"></div>
<h2>Conversion rate benchmarks for Facebook Ads</h2>
<p dir="ltr"><strong>The average conversion rate across Facebook Ad leads campaigns is <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/facebook-ads-benchmarks-2025" target="_blank" rel="noopener">7.72%</a>.Â </strong></p>
<div style="text-align: center;"></div>
<div><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/2025-fb-benchmarks-cvr-869x1024.webp" alt="2025 leads average conversion rate in meta ads" width="869" height="1024" class="aligncenter wp-image-93934 size-large" /></div>
<p dir="ltr">If youâ€™re responsible for marketing a bakery, bar, catering company, or some other restaurant or food-related business, failing to take advantage of Facebook Ads is a <em>huge</em> mistake. As you can see, the average advertiser in this industry converts clicks into meaningful actions at a rate of over 18%!</p>
<p>Advertisers within the industries of Attorneys and Legal Services, with a CVR of 10.53%, and Education and Instruction, with a CVR of 10.05% are doing great, too. Itâ€™s not a coincidence that businesses in each of these industries can benefit from the use of <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/how-to-optimize-facebook-lead-ads">Facebook lead ads</a>â€”an ad format that enables you to qualify prospects without sending them to an external landing page.</p>
<p>Clearly, however, Facebook lead ads are no silver bullet: Although advertisers in Furniture (3.77%), Physicians and Surgeons (4.51%), and Home and Home Improvement (5.22%) industries can certainly take advantage of this frictionless format, they might struggle to drive conversions nonetheless. For these businesses in particular, remarketing would be a fantastic use of the Facebook platform.</p>
