</ul>
<p>Letâ€™s look at how to create these types of irresistible CTAs.</p>
<div id="how-to-write-a-call-to-action"></div>
<h2>How do you write a good call to action?</h2>
<p>A <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/how-pros-write-calls-to-action">good call to action</a> will attract attention and make it hard to resist taking the next step in ads, emails, landing pages, and more. Read on to learn how to write CTAs that drive conversions no matter where they are (see what we did there?).</p>
<h3>1. Use a strong verb to start your CTA</h3>
<p>You donâ€™t have a ton of space to get your point across. Donâ€™t dilly or dally. Let your audience know exactly what you want them to do by leading each <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2015/02/20/call-to-action-buttons">CTA button</a> with an action verb.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/call-to-action-example-lockin.jpg" alt="call to action - screenshot of a call to action page promoting free gift" width="936" height="571" class="aligncenter wp-image-76601 size-full" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/call-to-action-example-lockin.jpg 936w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/call-to-action-example-lockin-480x293.jpg 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 936px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>There are different action verbs depending on the type of business you run and what you want your customer to do. Here are a few ideas:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>For an ecommerce website:</strong> Start your CTA with words like â€œbuy,â€ â€œshop,â€ or â€œorderâ€</li>
<li><strong>If youâ€™re promoting a newsletter or piece of content:</strong> Start your CTA with words like â€œdownloadâ€ or â€œsubscribeâ€</li>
<li><b>For a service-based business:</b> Try CTAs that begin with â€œcall nowâ€ or â€œbook your appointment.â€</li>
</ul>
<p>What you donâ€™t want is to simply say something exists. â€œOur newest fashions are availableâ€ wonâ€™t stir people to action, whereas â€œclick here for the latest trendsâ€ feels kinetic and is more likely to improve your <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/click-through-rate">click-through rate</a>.</p>
<h3>2. Include words that provoke emotion or enthusiasm</h3>
<p>If you want more clicks and conversions, you need to elicit a strong response from your audience. An enthusiastic CTA that taps into <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2021/05/03/emotional-marketing-copy">emotional copywriting</a> is just the thing to get it done.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/call-to-action-example-donedone.jpg" alt="call to action - screenshot of a landing page from brand Done Done" width="817" height="583" class="aligncenter wp-image-76602 size-full" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/call-to-action-example-donedone.jpg 817w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/call-to-action-example-donedone-480x343.jpg 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 817px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>Letâ€™s say someone is looking to book a trip with their family. They come across a CTA like â€œplan your dream vacation today!â€ Thatâ€™ll get them hyped and thinking about what their dream vacation looks like. Theyâ€™ll eagerly click the link in your ad.</p>
<p>Some other ways your CTAs can <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2021/01/13/best-words-and-phrases-for-marketing">tap into emotion include</a>:</p>
<ul>
<li>Reducing risk and insecurity</li>
<li>Building trust</li>
<li>Creating urgency</li>
<li>Communication value</li>
</ul>
<p>Donâ€™t forget punctuation. Add an exclamation point to the end of your CTA to max out the excitement. Itâ€™ll make your CTA pop and give it a little extra kick.</p>
<h3>3. Give your audience a reason to act</h3>
<p>In other words, tell people whatâ€™s in it for them if they click. Will it help them do their jobs better, lose weight, or save money? This will tie in heavily with your value proposition, or <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2014/04/07/unique-selling-proposition">unique selling point</a> (USP). Your USP is arguably one of the most important pieces of acquiring new leads, so creating a nice USP/CTA mash-up is a great way to increase clicks.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/call-to-action-example-slider.jpg" alt="call to action - screenshot of landing page with CTA from brand slider" width="842" height="589" class="aligncenter wp-image-76603 size-full" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/call-to-action-example-slider.jpg 842w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/call-to-action-example-slider-480x336.jpg 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 842px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>A good <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2022/04/13/call-to-action-examples">example of a call to action</a> here would be something like â€œcall us to start saving money today!â€ Not only have you stated the action you want the user to take (call today), but you have also provided them with a reason why they should take that action (save money).</p>
<h3>4. Take advantage of FOMO</h3>
<p>This is actually one of my favorite tactics when it comes to a successful CTA. Fear of missing out, otherwise known as <a href="http://psychcentral.com/blog/archives/2011/04/14/fomo-addiction-the-fear-of-missing-out/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">FOMO</a>, is an extremely effective motivator. When people think they might lose out on an opportunity that might not come around again, theyâ€™ll be mighty quick to hop on the bandwagon.</p>
<p>One of the best uses of FOMO in your CTA is to mention a sale or promotion that your company is holding, and which wonâ€™t last forever.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/call-to-action-example-curbside-1.jpg" alt="call to action - Screenshot of an ad with CTA for shop now" width="370" height="600" class="aligncenter wp-image-76604 size-full" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/call-to-action-example-curbside-1.jpg 370w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/call-to-action-example-curbside-1-185x300.jpg 185w" sizes="(max-width: 370px) 100vw, 370px" /></p>
<p>You probably get emails with this sort of messaging all the time, I know I sure do. Iâ€™m talking about messaging like â€œShop today! Sale ends on Monday,â€ perhaps during a three-day weekend. Or even â€œbuy now while supplies last!â€ during the holiday season. Itâ€™s tough to ignore a prompt like that, especially during a time-sensitive, under-the-gun type of situation (e.g. the Christmas season).</p>
<p>Similar to provoking enthusiasm as we discussed earlier, provoking fear of missing out in your CTA is sure to get you some additional clicks.</p>
<h3>5. Match CTA to device type</h3>
<p>Creating a killer call-to-action is important, thatâ€™s no secret. But I also urge you to consider customizing your CTA based on the device being used by your audience. Google considers <a href="http://searchengineland.com/the-real-reason-why-google-is-dropping-the-tablet-vs-desktop-distinction-its-the-user-context-stupid-149738" target="_blank" rel="noopener">desktop and tablet as the same device</a>, since the screen sizes are roughly the same. People also use them for search in similar scenarios.</p>
<p>For example, someone sitting on the couch at night sees an ad on TV for a product theyâ€™re interested in. Itâ€™s common for them to grab their laptop or tablet and search for more information on it. It might be best to lead them with a â€œlearn moreâ€ or â€œshop nowâ€ CTA.</p>
<p>However, <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2014/08/18/mobile-ad-strategies">mobile devices tend to have different user behavior</a> and search intent than desktop/tablets. Since <a href="https://localiq.com/blog/local-seo-statistics/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">80%</a> of searches for local business on mobile devices convert, itâ€™s prudent to tailor your CTA based on device..</p>
<p>One big difference between desktop and mobile is that on mobile, people have the ability to place a call from the device theyâ€™re shopping with. My advice is to create more phone call-centric CTAs that appear on mobile devices, especially for service-based businesses. This lawn care company has a clickable phone number on their landing page.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/call-to-action-example-landscape.jpg" alt="call to action - screenshot of a landscapers website with clickable phone number" width="356" height="595" class="aligncenter wp-image-76605 size-full" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/call-to-action-example-landscape.jpg 356w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/call-to-action-example-landscape-179x300.jpg 179w" sizes="(max-width: 356px) 100vw, 356px" /></p>
<p>Some possible <a href="https://localiq.com/blog/powerful-call-to-action-phrases/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">CTA phrases</a> to try could be â€œcall now to get startedâ€ or â€œcall us today for more informationâ€ to guide your target audience to take the action you want them to take.</p>
<h3>6. A/B test your CTAs</h3>
<p>A good, old-fashioned <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2012/09/25/a-b-testing">A/B test</a> is a great way to identify which CTAâ€™s bring you clicks, and which CTAâ€™s bring you frowns. While your tried and true <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2014/10/20/call-to-action-examples">calls-to-action</a> like the ones weâ€™ve already discussed are always good to use, you really never know how theyâ€™ll perform in your account until you actually use them.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/call-to-action-example-dewalt.jpg" alt="call to action - Comparision of two ads from Dewalt" width="926" height="384" class="aligncenter wp-image-76606 size-full" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/call-to-action-example-dewalt.jpg 926w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/call-to-action-example-dewalt-480x199.jpg 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 926px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>Digital marketing is definitely a game of trial and error (which is why it can be frustrating!), and your calls-to-action are no exception to the rule. Something could look great on paper, or may sound great when a colleague recommends it to you, but the only way youâ€™ll absolutely know for sure if something will work for your account is if you test it out.</p>
<p>Your target audience may not respond well to what could be considered a â€œsurefire CTA,â€ which is enough to make you pull your hair out. By A/B testing, you can trial some <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2010/09/29/unusual-effective-calls-to-action">creative CTAs</a> and compare them to your old standards. If your target audience isnâ€™t responding well to your ads, you might as well try to think outside the box a bit!</p>
<p>Start with:</p>
<ul>
<li>Check out todayâ€™s deals!</li>
<li>Fill out a form to get started</li>
<li>Call today for more information</li>
</ul>
<p>And test against:</p>
<ul>
<li>Tons of deals at your fingertips</li>
<li>A healthier life starts now!</li>
<li>Donâ€™t miss out, call us today!</li>
</ul>
<h3>7. Add numbers when possible</h3>
<ol start="7"></ol>
<p>We consumers respond well to seeing numbers such as pricing, discounts, promotions, incentives, etc. It helps us to determine whether or not itâ€™s worth splurging on items we desperately want, but probably arenâ€™t essential to everyday life. So when the opportunity arises, why not appeal to your target audience that way?</p>
<p>I am always a big proponent of including pricing information in your ad copy in general, and that includes your CTA. If a user sees your pricing information in your ad, and decides to click through to your site, then you know they are still interested in the product or service you are offering. Now you know you have yourself a valuable click, and an increased chance at generating a conversion.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/call-to-action-example-luna.jpg" alt="call to action - landing page from brand Luna with subscribe CTA" width="557" height="584" class="wp-image-76607 size-full aligncenter" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/call-to-action-example-luna.jpg 557w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/call-to-action-example-luna-480x503.jpg 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 557px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>But, if you donâ€™t include your pricing information in your ads, someone may click through to your site, excited about your products/services, but then get scared off by your prices. Now you have yourself a less than desirable situation. This leads to the dreaded wasted spend in your account, and who wants to deal with that?</p>
<p>Try experimenting with your pricing information in your CTA, as well as any other applicable numerical information. A CTA such as â€œShop today for TVs under $300!â€ not only shows a user how little they will pay for a TV, but it also hits on the FOMO element as well (pretty sneaky huh?).</p>
<p>If you run a special promotion for shipping, you could try something like â€œorder by Sunday for 1-day shipping.â€ Maybe you are an auto body shop looking to incentivize your audience with a discount; your CTA might look something like â€œBook today! 15% off your next visit.â€</p>
<p><img src="https://s.w.org/images/core/emoji/16.0.1/72x72/1f44b.png" alt="ðŸ‘‹" class="wp-smiley" style="height: 1em; max-height: 1em;" /> Want more tips on creating ads that convert? Get your copy of our free <a href="https://marketing.wordstream.com/WSContentDLWebBlogInContentTextLinkAllStarPlaybook.html?cid=Web_Blog_InContent_TextLink_AllStarPlaybook_Download">all-star playbook for online advertising</a>.</p>
<h3>8. Be bold in your CTA copy</h3>
<p>This can be a little risquÃ©, but adding a dash of brash to your CTA copy can be pretty effective in catching someoneâ€™s eye.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/call-to-action-example-unspam.jpg" alt="call to action - screenshot of an ad for a conference with a bold CTA" width="789" height="587" class="aligncenter wp-image-76608 size-full" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/call-to-action-example-unspam.jpg 789w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/10/call-to-action-example-unspam-480x357.jpg 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 789px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>One option that can be tough to pull off is using negative words to motivate a person to change something they are self-conscious about. For example, if I was on Google looking to lose weight and saw a call-to-action such as â€œend your crappy diet today,â€ I might just want to click. Sure, itâ€™s a bit over-the-top, which is why I recommend using this technique sparingly, but it definitely commands attention.</p>
<p>Hereâ€™s another example. Say I want to fix the brown patches in my lawn. Iâ€™m perusing Google and see an ad with a CTA like â€œyour yard sucks, let us fix it.â€ Not only would I probably chuckle, but I would also probably click just to see exactly what that lawn company could do for me. Youâ€™re walking a fine line with this technique, but it can pay off.</p>
<h3>Boost conversions with strong calls to action</h3>
<p>Whether itâ€™s on your website, social media ads, search engine listings, or newsletter, a well-written call to action will get more people to take the next step toward making a purchase.</p>
<p>Remember these eight tips to write a good call to action:</p>
<ol>
<li>Use a strong verb to start your CTA</li>
<li>Include words that provoke emotion or enthusiasm</li>
<li>Give your audience a reason to act</li>
<li>Take advantage of FOMO</li>
<li>Match CTA to device type</li>
<li>A/B test your CTAs</li>
<li>Add numbers when possible</li>
<li>Be bold in your CTA</li>
</ol>
<p>The post <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2014/10/09/call-to-action">How to Write a Killer Call to Action: 8 Tips &#038; Ideas</a> appeared first on <a href="https://www.wordstream.com">WordStream</a>.</p>
