<h2>3. Include all types of social proof</h2>
<p>Whether we want to admit it or not, the social standing of a product or service plays a role in whether someone will want to convert on your site or not. Be sure to include any instances of <a href="https://localiq.com/blog/what-is-social-proof/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">social proof</a> you can come up with and allow those insights to do some of your promotional work for you. Here are some examples of what those could look like, sticking with the Jackery site to keep the example running.</p>
<h3>Customer reviews</h3>
<p>I honestly believe one of the most impactful selling points of a product or service is the <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2020/09/16/get-more-google-reviews">reviews</a> of previous customers. People arenâ€™t shy about sharing their opinions online, so when you can have an overwhelmingly positive set of statements from customers, that goes a long way.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/increase-conversion-rates-customer-reviews.jpg" alt="increase conversion rates - example of customer reviews on product landing page to help drive conversion rates up" width="700" height="598" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-75898" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/increase-conversion-rates-customer-reviews.jpg 700w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/increase-conversion-rates-customer-reviews-480x410.jpg 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 700px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>This is just one review from the Jackery site, but they have quite a few that look like this as well. You can visually see the 4.9/5 star rating that shows up and the highlighted bars in the columns in the middle very easily on the site because theyâ€™re yellow, which stands apart from the siteâ€™s main orange and dark gray theme. And even though when you look closer and see there are only 32 reviews, itâ€™s still pretty compelling that there are no reviews lower than a 4 on this product.</p>
<h3>Major media mentions</h3>
<p>Another good social proof signal is including any major publication or media mentions your company or products have.</p>
<p>Unfortunately for my example, Jackery doesnâ€™t have this option (or the next) on their landing page, but it does live on the <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2016/05/27/guide-to-about-us-pages">About page</a> on the site.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/increase-conversion-rates-media-mentions.jpg" alt="increase conversion rates - include media mentions and major organizational partners" width="936" height="442" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-75899" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/increase-conversion-rates-media-mentions.jpg 936w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/increase-conversion-rates-media-mentions-480x227.jpg 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 936px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>Including these gives credibility by affiliating you with other brands that users likely have heard of before, especially if that publication has lots of clout in a specific area.</p>
<p>For the logos above, as a person interested in green portable solar power, I find the mentions from Outdoor Life and National Forest Foundation to be particularly interesting. Iâ€™m also an amateur photographer, so the mention from Digital Camera World is also nice to see. You never know what publications will pique someoneâ€™s interest, so be sure to include any potential options on your site.</p>
<h3>Awards, ratings, and certifications</h3>
<p>Also found on the About page of the Jackery site is a quick overview of their certifications and <a href="https://localiq.com/blog/how-to-promote-business-award/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">awards</a>.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/increase-conversion-rates-awards.jpg" alt="increase conversion rates - include awards and certifications - example from jackery" width="936" height="386" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-75900" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/increase-conversion-rates-awards.jpg 936w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/increase-conversion-rates-awards-480x198.jpg 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 936px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>Just like the media outlet mentions, these can be compelling for folks who are familiar with the field and help give your business credibility. Extra points if your competition doesnâ€™t have similar awards for comparison.</p>
<h2>4. Set expectations for the conversion process</h2>
<p>Many customers will feel more comfortable taking a <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2022/08/03/improve-conversion-rates">conversion action</a> if they know whatâ€™s coming next. If theyâ€™ve never worked with your company before, this can help put them at least and, potentially, help prevent them from contacting your customer support prematurely or unnecessarily.</p>
<p>For an ecommerce account, this might seem a little strange. Add a product to cart, check out, it shows up at your door, right? Not quite.</p>
<p>How long will it take for you to package the product and get it in the mail? How long will it take once itâ€™s there? Do you need to have someone ready to sign for the product or can it be dropped off at a door?</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/increase-conversion-rates-communicate-conversion-path.jpg" alt="increase conversion rates - communicate conversion path - example from zok" width="936" height="600" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-75902" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/increase-conversion-rates-communicate-conversion-path.jpg 936w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/increase-conversion-rates-communicate-conversion-path-480x308.jpg 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 936px, 100vw" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><em><a href="https://zokrelief.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Source</a></em></p>
<p>For <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2023/01/12/how-to-generate-leads">lead generation</a>, this is even more important. Once a prospect fills out a form, how long will it be before they hear from you? In what format will they hear from you: phone call, email, calendar invite? Do they need to have anything prepped for that point of contact and what are the steps after that touch point?</p>
<p>When customers know what to expect, itâ€™s easier for them to visualize working with you, making it more likely for them to convert.</p>
<h2>5. Include multiple ways for users to convert</h2>
<p>The conversion action you use will have a great impact on your <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2019/08/19/conversion-rate-benchmarks">conversion rates</a>.</p>
<p>A very common â€œbest practiceâ€ with <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/conversion-rate-optimization">conversion rate optimization</a> is to include only one call to action on your landing page. This is intended to help avoid confusion and provide only one way forward (or backward) for the user to go. In some instances, this can help folks who want more information to convert but donâ€™t have another path to take.</p>
<p>Personally, Iâ€™m a little allergic to that approach. While I certainly agree you can have a single call to action as the primary focus of a page, I donâ€™t know if I agree with the fact that you should only ever have one action per page and never add a second.</p>
<p>All potential customers are different. Some like to conduct all their actions online. Others want to have a phone call. Some prefer to make a purchase in person. None of these people are â€œwrong,â€ they just have their ways of doing business.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/increase-conversion-rates-multiple-ctas.jpg" alt="increase conversion rates - add multiple ctas" width="936" height="568" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-75909" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/increase-conversion-rates-multiple-ctas.jpg 936w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/increase-conversion-rates-multiple-ctas-480x291.jpg 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 936px, 100vw" /></p>
<p style="text-align: center;"><em><a href="https://www.midtowndentistrydallas.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">This dentist</a> provides a phone number, a &#8220;request an appointment&#8221; button, or an option to request an appointment via chat.</em></p>
<p>If you choose to include only one form of conversion on the page, say a form fill for example, youâ€™re alienating the users who would rather chat on the phone or come directly to your store.</p>
<p>If possible, I suggest always having a few different ways for users to get in touch with you, even if theyâ€™re found on other pages of the site, and simply <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2023/02/08/google-ads-conversion-tracking-mistakes">track all of those actions</a>.</p>
<p>For Ecommerce, this might seem like a miss, but I think this applies to online sales as well.</p>
<p>Again, some people are fine adding their credit card information to any site, but others are more weary of individual businesses having that data. Theyâ€™d prefer to use a brand they trust like PayPal or Apple Pay. For retailers, I always suggest accepting multiple different forms of payment (assuming fees arenâ€™t too daunting) to capture all of your potential market.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/increase-conversion-rates-forms-of-conversions.jpg" alt="increase conversion rates - examples of payment methods accepted on product landing page" width="891" height="600" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-75901" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/increase-conversion-rates-forms-of-conversions.jpg 891w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/increase-conversion-rates-forms-of-conversions-480x323.jpg 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 891px, 100vw" /></p>
<h2>6. Minimize required fields</h2>
<p>My last suggestion for increasing conversion rates is to think about what information you really need to call someone a conversion. Do you need their name, email, and phone number? Do you need their job title and the company they work for? Do you need their home address, city, state, and zip code?</p>
<p>Now stop and think, to follow up with someone, do you <em>really need </em>all of that information, or would it just be nice to have?</p>
<p>Asking for some of those â€œnice to haveâ€ pieces is great, but if you go overboard with too long of a form, you risk irritating someone and asking too much of them.</p>
<p>The example that drives me the most nuts is city, state, and zip code. If you have someoneâ€™s zip code, you can easily find their city and state. There are tools that do that automatically. Stop asking for all three fields when one will suffice.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" src="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/increase-conversion-rates-limited-form-fields.jpg" alt="increase conversion rates - limited form field example" width="936" height="600" class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-75908" srcset="https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/increase-conversion-rates-limited-form-fields.jpg 936w, https://www.wordstream.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/increase-conversion-rates-limited-form-fields-480x308.jpg 480w" sizes="(min-width: 0px) and (max-width: 480px) 480px, (min-width: 481px) 936px, 100vw" /></p>
<p>Limit your forms to only the information you actually <em>need</em> to follow up with someone and leave the â€œnice to havesâ€ for future sales conversations.</p>
<h2>Increase conversion rates with these simple tweaks</h2>
<p>Thereâ€™s no singular tactic that is guaranteed to <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/winter-content-ideas">increase your conversion rates</a>. Youâ€™ll even notice that some of my suggestions here might seem to be contradictory. Put lots of useful information on the page, but also make sure itâ€™s concise and loads quickly. Provide lots of ways for people to convert but also limit what you ask them for in that conversion process. Add and take away. Each of these is a tactic that Iâ€™ve seen work in the past. Now itâ€™s up to you to test and find out which will work for your company.</p>
<p>The post <a href="https://www.wordstream.com/blog/ws/2023/09/11/increase-conversion-rates">6 Non-Obvious (Yet Simple) Strategies to Increase Conversion Rates</a> appeared first on <a href="https://www.wordstream.com">WordStream</a>.</p>
]]></content:encoded>
					
		
		
